{
  "Primary producers in most ecosystems obtain their energy from:": "",
  "Absorbing minerals from the soil": "",
  "Decomposing dead organic matter": "",
  "Consuming other organisms": "",
  "Sunlight through photosynthesis": "",
  "Primary producers (autotrophs) convert solar energy into chemical energy through photosynthesis. They form the base of most food webs and provide the energy that flows through all trophic levels.": "",
  "Approximately what percentage of energy is typically transferred from one trophic level to the next?": "",
  "90%": "",
  "1%": "",
  "10%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "The 10% rule states that roughly 10% of the energy at one trophic level is transferred to the next. The remaining 90% is lost as heat through cellular respiration, used in metabolism, or remains unconsumed.": "",
  "The carbon cycle includes all of the following processes EXCEPT:": "",
  "Cellular respiration": "",
  "Combustion of fossil fuels": "",
  "Photosynthesis": "",
  "Nitrogen fixation": "",
  "Nitrogen fixation converts atmospheric nitrogen into ammonia and is part of the nitrogen cycle, not the carbon cycle. The carbon cycle involves photosynthesis, respiration, decomposition, combustion, and ocean dissolution.": "",
  "Decomposers play a critical role in ecosystems by:": "",
  "Fixing atmospheric nitrogen into usable forms": "",
  "Producing oxygen through photosynthesis": "",
  "Converting sunlight into chemical energy": "",
  "Breaking down dead organisms and recycling nutrients back into the ecosystem": "",
  "Decomposers (bacteria and fungi) break down dead organic matter, releasing nutrients (nitrogen, phosphorus, carbon) back into the soil, water, and atmosphere. Without decomposers, nutrients would remain locked in dead organisms.": "",
  "Gross primary productivity (GPP) differs from net primary productivity (NPP) because:": "",
  "NPP includes energy from decomposers": "",
  "GPP only measures animal production": "",
  "NPP equals GPP minus the energy used by producers for their own cellular respiration": "",
  "GPP is always smaller than NPP": "",
  "GPP is the total amount of energy fixed by photosynthesis. NPP = GPP - R (respiration by producers). NPP represents the energy available to consumers and decomposers, and it is always less than GPP.": "",
  "In the nitrogen cycle, nitrogen fixation converts:": "",
  "Ammonia into nitrate": "",
  "Nitrate into atmospheric nitrogen": "",
  "Atmospheric nitrogen (N₂) into ammonia (NH₃)": "",
  "Organic nitrogen into atmospheric nitrogen": "",
  "Nitrogen fixation converts atmospheric N₂ gas into ammonia (NH₃), a form usable by plants. This is carried out primarily by certain bacteria (e.g., Rhizobium in root nodules of legumes) and by lightning.": "",
  "Why are food chains typically limited to 4-5 trophic levels?": "",
  "Higher trophic levels are always occupied by decomposers": "",
  "Predators at higher levels reproduce too slowly": "",
  "Energy loss at each level (approximately 90%) leaves insufficient energy to support additional levels": "",
  "There are not enough species to fill more levels": "",
  "With only about 10% of energy transferred between trophic levels, there is progressively less energy available to support organisms at higher levels. By the 4th or 5th level, there is insufficient energy to sustain another trophic level.": "",
  "The water cycle is driven primarily by:": "",
  "Volcanic activity releasing water vapor": "",
  "Gravitational pull of the moon": "",
  "Solar energy driving evaporation and transpiration": "",
  "Chemical reactions between water and minerals": "",
  "Solar energy heats water, causing evaporation from oceans, lakes, and soil, and transpiration from plants. Water vapor rises, condenses into clouds, and returns to Earth as precipitation, completing the cycle.": "",
  "Biological magnification (biomagnification) occurs when:": "",
  "Nutrients are recycled more efficiently at higher trophic levels": "",
  "Organisms at higher trophic levels have larger body sizes": "",
  "Populations increase at each trophic level": "",
  "Toxins become increasingly concentrated in organisms at higher trophic levels": "",
  "Biomagnification occurs when persistent toxins (like DDT or mercury) that are not metabolized accumulate in organisms' tissues and become increasingly concentrated at higher trophic levels because predators consume many contaminated prey.": "",
  "Which biogeochemical cycle does NOT have a significant atmospheric component?": "",
  "Water cycle": "",
  "Nitrogen cycle": "",
  "Carbon cycle": "",
  "Phosphorus cycle": "",
  "The phosphorus cycle is primarily sedimentary, cycling through rocks, soil, water, and organisms. Unlike carbon and nitrogen, phosphorus does not have a significant gaseous phase and moves through ecosystems primarily in dissolved or solid forms.": "",
  "What is a 'trophic level'?": "",
  "The geographic level at which a species lives in the ecosystem": "",
  "A feeding position in a food chain or food web, defined by the number of energy-transfer steps from producers": "",
  "The amount of water available at each level of an ecosystem": "",
  "The temperature at each level of the atmosphere": "",
  "A trophic level is a position in a food chain defined by the number of energy transfers from the base. Producers are the first trophic level, primary consumers the second, secondary consumers the third, and so on.": "",
  "What does 'primary productivity' mean?": "",
  "The rate at which producers convert solar energy into chemical energy (biomass) through photosynthesis": "",
  "The rate at which consumers eat producers": "",
  "The rate of decomposition in an ecosystem": "",
  "The total number of species in an ecosystem": "",
  "Primary productivity is the rate at which autotrophs capture and store energy. It sets the energy budget for the entire ecosystem and determines how much energy is available to support consumers at higher trophic levels.": "",
  "What does 'biogeochemical cycle' mean?": "",
  "The chemical reactions that occur inside cells": "",
  "The life cycle of a single organism": "",
  "The cycle of day and night caused by Earth's rotation": "",
  "The pathway by which chemical elements and compounds move through both living organisms and the abiotic environment": "",
  "Biogeochemical cycles describe the movement of essential elements (carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus, water) through biological (living organisms), geological (rocks, soil), and chemical (reactions) components of ecosystems.": "",
  "What is 'net primary productivity' (NPP)?": "",
  "The amount of dead organic matter in an ecosystem": "",
  "The energy produced by consumers at the top of the food chain": "",
  "The total energy fixed by producers minus the energy they use for their own respiration, representing energy available to consumers": "",
  "The total energy fixed by all organisms in the ecosystem": "",
  "NPP = GPP - R (producer respiration). It represents the amount of energy actually stored as biomass by producers and available for consumption by herbivores, decomposers, and higher trophic levels.": "",
  "What does 'nitrogen fixation' mean?": "",
  "The release of nitrogen gas into the atmosphere": "",
  "The absorption of nitrogen by animals": "",
  "The conversion of atmospheric nitrogen gas (N₂) into biologically usable forms of nitrogen such as ammonia (NH₃)": "",
  "The conversion of ammonia into nitrite": "",
  "Nitrogen fixation is the process of converting inert atmospheric N₂ into ammonia, which organisms can incorporate into organic compounds. It is performed primarily by nitrogen-fixing bacteria, either free-living or in symbiosis with legumes.": "",
  "What is 'biomagnification'?": "",
  "The magnification of organisms under a microscope": "",
  "The increasing concentration of persistent toxins in organisms at successively higher trophic levels in a food chain": "",
  "The increase in body size at each trophic level": "",
  "The increase in biodiversity at higher trophic levels": "",
  "Biomagnification occurs when non-degradable toxins accumulate through the food chain. At each trophic level, a consumer ingests the toxins from many prey organisms, concentrating the toxin in its own tissues.": "",
  "What does 'denitrification' mean?": "",
  "The conversion of nitrates back into atmospheric nitrogen gas (N₂) by bacteria, returning nitrogen to the atmosphere": "",
  "The oxidation of ammonia to nitrite": "",
  "The uptake of nitrogen by plant roots": "",
  "The conversion of atmospheric nitrogen into ammonia": "",
  "Denitrification is the anaerobic process by which denitrifying bacteria convert nitrates (NO₃⁻) in soil back into nitrogen gas (N₂) or nitrous oxide (N₂O), which is released into the atmosphere, completing the nitrogen cycle.": "",
  "What is an 'energy pyramid'?": "",
  "A representation of the number of species at each altitude within the broader context of energy analysis": "",
  "A diagram showing the relative amount of energy at each trophic level, with producers forming the broad base and top consumers at the narrow apex": "",
  "A graph showing energy prices over time without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "A pyramid-shaped structure where organisms live under most circumstances involving energy": "",
  "An energy pyramid (ecological pyramid of energy) shows the amount of energy available at each trophic level. It is always wider at the base (producers) and narrows at each successive level due to the approximately 90% energy loss at each transfer.": "",
  "What does 'nitrification' mean?": "",
  "The oxidation of ammonia (NH₃) to nitrite (NO₂⁻) and then to nitrate (NO₃⁻) by nitrifying bacteria": "",
  "The incorporation of nitrogen into organic molecules by plants": "",
  "Nitrification is a two-step aerobic process: first, Nitrosomonas bacteria oxidize ammonia to nitrite, then Nitrobacter bacteria oxidize nitrite to nitrate. Nitrate is the form of nitrogen most readily absorbed by plant roots.": "",
  "What does 'carbon sink' mean?": "",
  "A place where carbon is released into the atmosphere": "",
  "The total amount of carbon on Earth": "",
  "A reservoir that absorbs and stores more carbon than it releases, effectively removing carbon from the atmosphere": "",
  "A type of kitchen sink made from carbon fiber": "",
  "A carbon sink is a natural or artificial reservoir that absorbs more carbon than it releases. Forests, oceans, and soil are major carbon sinks. They help regulate atmospheric CO₂ levels and mitigate climate change.": "",
  "A lake receives excess nitrogen and phosphorus from agricultural runoff. Within months, algal blooms cover the surface, and fish begin dying. What process is occurring, and why are fish dying?": "",
  "The fish are dying of starvation because they cannot eat algae": "",
  "The algae are directly toxic to all fish species": "",
  "Biomagnification is concentrating toxins in the fish": "",
  "Eutrophication: excess nutrients cause algal overgrowth; when algae die, decomposers consume dissolved oxygen, creating hypoxic conditions that kill fish": "",
  "Eutrophication occurs when excess nutrients stimulate massive algal growth. When the algae die, decomposing bacteria consume enormous amounts of dissolved oxygen, creating dead zones where oxygen levels are too low for fish and other aerobic organisms to survive.": "",
  "A farmer grows soybeans (a legume) in a field that previously had low nitrogen. After the soybean harvest, the soil nitrogen levels are significantly higher. What biological process explains this increase?": "",
  "Nitrogen-fixing bacteria (Rhizobium) in the soybean root nodules converted atmospheric N₂ into ammonia, enriching the soil": "",
  "The soybeans absorbed nitrogen from the atmosphere through their leaves": "",
  "Denitrifying bacteria added nitrogen to the soil": "",
  "The soybeans decomposed and released stored nitrogen": "",
  "Legumes form a mutualistic relationship with Rhizobium bacteria in root nodules. These bacteria fix atmospheric N₂ into NH₃, which the plant uses. When the plant dies or sheds roots, this fixed nitrogen enriches the soil, which is why legumes are used in crop rotation.": "",
  "An ecologist measures that a forest produces 20,000 kcal/m²/year of gross primary productivity and the plants use 12,000 kcal/m²/year for their own respiration. What is the net primary productivity, and how much energy is available to herbivores?": "",
  "NPP = 20,000 kcal/m²/year; all of GPP is available to herbivores": "",
  "NPP = 32,000 kcal/m²/year; all is available to herbivores": "",
  "NPP = 8,000 kcal/m²/year; approximately 800 kcal/m²/year reaches herbivores considering 10% transfer efficiency": "",
  "NPP = 12,000 kcal/m²/year; half goes to herbivores": "",
  "NPP = GPP - R = 20,000 - 12,000 = 8,000 kcal/m²/year. With approximately 10% transfer efficiency between trophic levels, about 800 kcal/m²/year would be available to herbivores (secondary productivity).": "",
  "DDT, a persistent pesticide, was sprayed in lakes to control mosquitoes in the 1960s. Scientists later found that fish-eating birds like ospreys had DDT concentrations millions of times higher than the lake water. What process caused this extreme concentration, and why were top predators most affected?": "",
  "Biomagnification concentrated DDT at each trophic level because the toxin is not metabolized, so top predators accumulate the highest concentrations": "",
  "Ospreys absorbed DDT directly from the air while flying": "",
  "DDT naturally moves upward through the atmosphere to where birds fly": "",
  "The ospreys were genetically predisposed to accumulate DDT": "",
  "Biomagnification occurs because DDT is lipophilic (fat-soluble) and persistent (not broken down). At each trophic level, organisms consume many contaminated prey, concentrating the toxin. Top predators eat the most contaminated organisms and thus accumulate the highest levels.": "",
  "Burning fossil fuels releases carbon that was stored underground for millions of years. How does this affect the global carbon cycle and climate?": "",
  "It removes carbon from the atmosphere, cooling the planet": "",
  "It only affects local ecosystems near power plants": "",
  "It has no effect because carbon is naturally recycled": "",
  "It adds carbon to the atmosphere faster than natural sinks can absorb it, increasing CO₂ concentrations and enhancing the greenhouse effect": "",
  "Fossil fuel combustion transfers geological carbon reserves into the atmosphere as CO₂ at a rate far exceeding natural removal by sinks. This excess CO₂ enhances the greenhouse effect, trapping more heat and driving global climate change.": "",
  "In a grassland ecosystem, producers contain 10,000 kcal of energy. Using the 10% rule, approximately how much energy would be available to a tertiary consumer (fourth trophic level)?": "",
  "100 kcal": "",
  "10 kcal": "",
  "1,000 kcal": "",
  "1 kcal": "",
  "Applying the 10% rule across three transfers: producers (10,000) to primary consumers (1,000) to secondary consumers (100) to tertiary consumers (10 kcal). This demonstrates why food chains rarely exceed 4-5 trophic levels.": "",
  "Deforestation in the Amazon reduces the forest's ability to act as a carbon sink. A scientist models the consequences. Which of the following correctly describes the cascading effects on the carbon cycle?": "",
  "The ocean will immediately compensate by absorbing all excess CO₂": "",
  "Reduced photosynthesis decreases CO₂ absorption, burning releases stored carbon, and decomposition of remaining organic matter adds more CO₂, all increasing atmospheric CO₂": "",
  "Deforestation has no effect on the carbon cycle": "",
  "Less CO₂ will be released because fewer trees means less respiration": "",
  "Deforestation affects the carbon cycle in three ways: (1) reduced photosynthesis decreases CO₂ uptake, (2) burning releases stored carbon as CO₂, and (3) decomposition of leftover organic matter releases additional CO₂. Combined, these significantly increase atmospheric CO₂.": "",
  "A researcher studies two lakes. Lake A receives no agricultural runoff and has clear water with diverse aquatic life. Lake B receives heavy phosphorus-laden runoff and has murky green water dominated by algae with few fish. What explains the difference, and what role does phosphorus play?": "",
  "Phosphorus is the limiting nutrient; excess phosphorus causes eutrophication, triggering algal blooms that block light and deplete oxygen when decomposed": "",
  "Lake B has more biodiversity because phosphorus promotes growth of all species": "",
  "Phosphorus is toxic to fish, directly killing them in Lake B": "",
  "The phosphorus runoff cooled Lake B, making it too cold for fish": "",
  "Phosphorus is often the limiting nutrient in freshwater ecosystems. Excess phosphorus from runoff removes this limitation, causing massive algal growth (eutrophication). When algae die, decomposition depletes oxygen, creating conditions inhospitable to fish.": "",
  "An ecologist argues that eating lower on the food chain (more plant-based diets) is more energy-efficient for feeding human populations. Using your knowledge of energy transfer between trophic levels, evaluate this claim.": "",
  "The claim is incorrect because meat is more energy-dense, since standard models of eating behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "The claim is incorrect because producers contain less energy than consumers in most scenarios involving eating factors": "",
  "The claim is correct because only about 10% of energy transfers between trophic levels, so consuming producers directly captures more of the original energy than consuming herbivores that ate producers": "",
  "The claim is irrelevant because humans are omnivores considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction together": "",
  "With the 10% rule, eating plants directly (first trophic level) captures roughly 10 times more energy per unit of producer biomass than eating herbivores. Feeding grain to cattle and then eating the cattle is inherently less efficient than eating the grain directly.": "",
  "Scientists discovered that adding iron to certain ocean regions stimulates massive phytoplankton blooms. Some have proposed ocean iron fertilization as a strategy to combat climate change. How would increased phytoplankton growth affect the carbon cycle, and what is a potential risk?": "",
  "Increased phytoplankton photosynthesis would absorb atmospheric CO₂, but a potential risk is that decomposition of the bloom could create ocean dead zones": "",
  "The phytoplankton would permanently remove all CO₂ from the atmosphere": "",
  "Iron fertilization would have no effect on the carbon cycle": "",
  "Phytoplankton would release more CO₂ through respiration, worsening climate change": "",
  "Phytoplankton fix CO₂ through photosynthesis, potentially drawing down atmospheric carbon. However, when the bloom dies, massive decomposition can deplete oxygen in deep water, creating dead zones. Additionally, the carbon may be re-released rather than permanently sequestered.": ""
}